[Leptospirosis has not been available in dog vaccines for a year or more,
depending upon the company the veterinarian purchased from and in what
quantity. If there is an increase, perhaps it is because we are no longer
vaccinating dogs for this very communicable disease.
Unfortunately, some animals such as cows, are less than sanitary, urinating
into and drinking from the same body of water. Dogs like to lay, splash and
drink from such bodies of water and may acquire the infection from whatever
domestic/wild animal may have had the disease and deposited into the water.
When areas are drought stricken, as much of the US has been, then organisms
can become concentrated into these ponds. The animals visit the water
depositing the organisms, the sun evaporates some of the water, and the
organisms are forced into a smaller volume of water.
In some states, a dog with leptospirosis is a reportable disease,
reportable to the health department. Although dogs rarely transmit the
disease to humans, it is an indication of an increase in the disease,
potentially causing concern for humans. - Mod.TG
